passages.text: Here are our key takeaways from the FY25 results conference call:

FY26 Guidance: PCA guide to \(2.9 - 9.2\%\) revenue growth into FY26. They commented that this assumed "modest market growth" in Australia - possibly consistent with what was seen in FY25 - and possibly assuming ongoing pressures in the UK, particularly in the remortgage market where a large portion of their International revenues come from.

Other UK large lenders to be a "fast follow": Management confirmed that they remain in conversation with Tier 1 lenders, but could not be drawn to comment further noting these conversations were "commercial in confidence". They did note that contingent on smooth progress with Natwest, other lenders would be a "fast follow". They did note having inbound from large banks following the Natwest announcement - but management reiterated they remain focussed on Natwest.

International cost growth ahead of revenue: Management noted that costs in International would continue to step up "slightly" ahead of revenues in FY26/27 as they continue to invest in operations to support bank partnerships and invest in sales and marketing.

Natwest go- forward plan - starting with existing Optima flows: Natwest will commence refinance volumes with their existing flow with Optima Legal which currently represents about \(8\%\) of Optima's flow. They commented that this flow would step up over FY26/7/8 as the capability is proven. They could not be drawn to comment on the revenue model (pricing is commercial in confidence), but noted that fee structure could be similar to what we see in Australia.

Platform investments: PEXA are looking to bring components of the UK platform architecture to Australia, which they noted is modular in nature and so would be faster to build, to test and to spot issues. They also noted leveraging this tech in a new product offering to support clients meet the new Anit- Money Laundering legislation in Australia - this could mean incremental revenues in the future. This will require ongoing capex.

Conveyancers are being engaged - but detail is scarce: Management commented that they were engaging with conveyancers, and were about to go on a national roadshow across the UK with a focus on meeting with and signing of conveyancers. This appears to be the focus. It sounds like they will be using the cash only market as a test case to demonstrate the functionality to conveyancers. But once again, they could not be drawn to comment on the number of conveyancers engaged so far, the revenue model, when we would see revenues or how conveyancers feel about possibly losing interest income on cash balances held in trust.

PEXA is the operator of the largest digital property settlements platform (PEXA Exchange) in Australia. PEXA Exchange is involved in \(\sim 90\%\) of all property transactions across Australia, and enjoys a monopolistic market position in e- conveyancing. We think there are limited near- term risks to this dominant market position, given ARNECC's announcement that it is pausing interpretability and standing down all project teams as well as Sympli's decision to move away from interoperability. PEXA is looking to replicate this success in the UK, and has recently achieved some key milestones which we think provide investors with incrementally improved confidence in PEXA's prospects for success in the UK. If PEXA is able to consistently deliver on its communicated milestones, we think the market will start placing value on its growth businesses.

Our 30 June 2026 price target of \(18.20 is based on our SOTP valuation using a 16.2x EBITDA multiple for each business (i.e. look through short- term volatility in ASX multiple), based on applying a \(12.5\%\) discount to the longer- term 18x EV/EBITDA multiple to allow for PEXA's higher CAPEX/EBITDA ratio.

PEXA (Overweight; Price Target: A\(18.20)

PEXA is the operator of the largest digital property settlements platform (PEXA Exchange) in Australia. PEXA Exchange is involved in \(\sim 90\%\) of all property transactions across Australia, and enjoys a monopolistic market position in e- conveyancing. We think there are limited near- term risks to this dominant market position, given ARNECC's announcement that it is pausing interpretability and standing down all project teams as well as Sympli's decision to move away from interoperability. PEXA is looking to replicate this success in the UK, and has recently achieved some key milestones which we think provide investors with incrementally improved confidence in PEXA's prospects for success in the UK. If PEXA is able to consistently deliver on its communicated milestones, we think the market will start placing value on its growth businesses.

Our 30 June 2026 price target of \(18.20 is based on our SOTP valuation. Our SoTP valuation adopts an ASX- type EV/EBITDA multiple adjusted for differences in CAPEX/EBITDA ratios (reflected in a \(\sim 12.5\%\) discount). We look through short- term fluctuations in the ASX multiple for this purpose, and adopt a longer- term 18x EV/EBITDA multiple before applying our \(12.5\%\) discount to arrive at our 16.2x valuation multiple for PEXA. For the International business, we assume a \(75\%\) probability of success for \(20\%\) market share at \(35\%\) EBITDA margins. We ascribe a value to the Digital solutions business given positive FY25 EBITDA expectations, but apply the same multiple as the other businesses given uncertainties in growth going forward. We separately allow for\) 50mn in expected additional CAPEX for the growth businesses.
